23/01/23, 09:36 - Gaurav Dave: #include<iostream>
#include<math.h>
using namespace std;

//class Calculator
class Calculator
{
    float a,b;
public:


    //functions to take input 
    void result()
    {
        cout << "----ENTER YOUR FIRST NUMBER----";
        cin >> a;
        cout << "----ENTER YOUR SECOND NUMBER----";
        cin >> b;
    }

        // Function to add two numbers
    float add()
    {
        return a + b;
    }

        // Function to subtract two numbers
    float sub()
    {
        return a - b;
    }

    // Function to multiply two numbers
    float mul()
    {
        return a * b;
    }

    //Function to divide two numbers
    float div(){
        if (b == 0)
        {
            cout << "Division by Zero" <<
            endl;
            return INFINITY;
        }
        else 
        {
            return a/b;
        }
    }
};

// Driver code
int main()
{
    int ch;
    Calculator c;
    cout << "Enter 1 to Add 2 Numbers" <<
            "\nEnter 2 to Subtract 2 Numbers" <<
            "\nEnter 3 to Multiply 2 Numbers" <<
            "\nEnter 4 to Divide 2 Numbers" <<
            "\nEnter 0 To Exit";

    do
    {
        cout << "\nEnter Choice: ";
        cin >> ch;
        switch (ch)
        {
          case 1:

            //result function invoke
            c.result();

            //add function invoke
            cout << "Result: " <<
            c.add() << endl;
            break;

          case 2:

          // sub function to calculate
            // difference
            c.result();
            cout << "Result: " <<
                    c.sub() << endl;
                    break;

            case 3:
            c.result();
             
            // mul function to calculate product
            cout << "Result: " <<
                     c.mul() << endl;
            break;
        case 4:
            c.result();
             
            // div function to calculate division
            cout << "Result: " <<
                     c.div() << endl;
            break;
        }
    }
    while (ch >= 1 && ch <= 4 );
    
    return 0;
}

25/01/23, 10:30 - Gaurav Dave: #include<iostream>
using namespace std;

class node
{
	char data[10];
	node*left;
	node*right;
	friend class binary_tree;
};

class binary_tree{
	node*root;
public:
	void create_tree();
};

void binary_tree::create_tree(){
	root = new node();
	cout<"Enter that data for root";
	cin>>root->data;
	root->left = root->right = NULL;
	node*curr,*temp;
	char choice,ch;

	do{
		curr = new node();
		temp = root;
		cout<<"Enter data";
		cin>>curr->data;
		curr->left = curr->right=NULL;
		int flag = 1;

		while(flag==1){
			cout<<"Insert data on left or right?"<<temp->data;
			cin>>ch;
			if(ch=='l'){
				if(temp->left==NULL){
					temp->left= curr;
					flag = 0;
					}

			else{
				flag=1;
				temp=temp->left;
			}
		}
			else if(ch=='r'){
				if(temp->right==NULL){
					temp->right=curr;
					flag=0;
					}
				else{
					flag=1;
					temp=temp->right;
				}
			}
		}
		cout<<"Enter y if you want to add more nodes";
		cin>>choice;
	}while(choice=='y');
	};

int main(){
	binary_tree t;
	t.create_tree();
	return 0;
}

30/01/23, 08:58 - Atharva: #include<iostream>
#include<string.h>
using namespace std;

class StudData;

class Student{
    string name;
    int roll_no;
    string cls;
    char* division;
    string dob;
    char* bloodgroup;
    static int count;

    public:

    Student()          // Default Constructor
    {
        name="";
        roll_no=0;
        cls="";
        division=new char;
        dob="dd/mm/yyyy";
        bloodgroup=new char[4];
    }

    ~Student()
    {
        delete division;
        delete[] bloodgroup;
    }

    static int getCount()
    {
        return count;
    }

    void getData(StudData*);
    void dispData(StudData*);
};

class StudData{
    string caddress;
    long int* telno;
    long int* dlno;
    friend class Student;

    public:

    StudData()
    {
        caddress="";
        telno=new long;
        dlno=new long;
    }
    
    ~StudData()
    {
        delete telno;
        delete dlno;
    }

    void getStudData()
    {
        cout<<"Enter Contact Address : ";
        cin.get();
        getline(cin,caddress);
        cout<<"Enter Telephone Number : ";
        cin>>*telno;
        cout<<"Enter Driving License Number : ";
        cin>>*dlno;
    }

    void dispStudData()
    {
        cout<<"Contact Address : "<<caddress<<endl;
        cout<<"Telephone Number : "<<*telno<<endl;
        cout<<"Driving License Number : "<<*dlno<<endl;
    }
};

inline void Student::getData(StudData* st)
{
    cout<<"Enter Student Name : ";
    getline(cin,name);
    cout<<"Enter Roll Number : ";
    cin>>roll_no;
    cout<<"Enter Class : ";
    cin.get();
    getline(cin,cls);
    cout<<"Enter Division : ";
    cin>>division;
    cout<<"Enter Date of Birth : ";
    cin.get();
    getline(cin,dob);
    cout<<"Enter Blood Group : ";
    cin>>bloodgroup;
    st->getStudData();
    count++;
}

inline void Student::dispData(StudData* st1)
{
    cout<<"Student Name : "<<name<<endl;
    cout<<"Roll Number : "<<roll_no<<endl;
    cout<<"Class : "<<cls<<endl;
    cout<<"Division : "<<division<<endl;
    cout<<"Date of Birth : "<<dob<<endl;
    cout<<"Blood Group : "<<bloodgroup<<endl;
    st1->dispStudData();
}

int Student::count;

int main()
{
    Student* stud1[100];
    StudData* stud2[100];
    int n=0;
    char ch;

    do
    {
        stud1[n]=new Student;
        stud2[n]=new StudData;
        stud1[n]->getData(stud2[n]);
        n++;
        cout<<"Do you want to add another student (y/n) : ";
        cin>>ch;
        cin.get();
    } while (ch=='y' || ch=='Y');

    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        cout<<"---------------------------------------------------------------"<<endl;
        stud1[i]->dispData(stud2[i]);
    }

    cout<<"---------------------------------------------------------------"<<endl;
    cout<<"Total Students : "<<Student::getCount();
    cout<<endl<<"---------------------------------------------------------------"<<endl;

    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        delete stud1[i];
        delete stud2[i];
    }
    

    return 0;
}
30/01/23, 09:07 - +91 93070 16245: Roll no. 15 Arvaan Vaswani

30/01/23, 09:30 - Atharva: HomeDevelop an object oriented program in C++ to create a database of student information systemDevelop an object oriented program in C++ to create a database of student information system
Develop an object oriented program in C++ to create a database of student information system
October 01, 2019
/*
Problem statement:
Develop an object oriented program in C++ to create a database of student information
system containing the following information: Name, Roll number, Class, division, Date of
Birth, Blood group, Contact address, telephone number, driving license no. etc Construct the
database with suitable member functions for initializing and destroying the data viz
constructor, default constructor, Copy constructor, destructor, static member functions, friend
class, this pointer, inline code and dynamic memory allocation operators-new and delete.
*/
#include<iostream>			//header file used for cin and cout
#include<string.h>			//header file for string class
using namespace std;			//refer cin and cout
#define max 100;
class per_info								//stud_info is friend class of per_info
{
    string lic, dob, bldgrp;    //personal info variables
    public:
    per_info();                 //DECLARE DEFAULT CONSTRUCTOR//
    per_info(per_info &);       //DECLARE COPY CONSTRUCTOR//
    ~per_info()                 //DEFINITION AND DECLARATION OF DESTRUCTOR
    {
          cout<<"\nDESTRUCTOR IS CALLED!!!!!"<<endl<<"RECORD DELETED SUCCESSFULLY"<<endl;
    }
    friend class student;                     //FRIEND FUNCTION DECLARATION
};
class student   							//DEFINITION OF STUDENT CLASS
{
    string name, address, year;				//OBJECTS OF STRING CLASS
    char div;
    int roll_no;
    long mob;
    static int cnt; 						//    STATIC VARIABLE DECLARATION
    public:
    void create(per_info &);				//TO CREATE DATABASE AND PASSED REFERENCE OF PERSONAL INFO OBJECT
    void display(per_info &);			//TO DISPLAY DATABASE
 
    inline static void inccnt()                //STATIC FUNCTION//
 
    {
      cnt++;
    }
    inline static void showcnt()               //STATIC FUNCTION//
                                      //INLINE FUNCTION//
    {
      cout<<"\nTOTAL NO OF RECORDS ARE : "<<cnt;
    }
    student();                           //DEFAULT CONSTRUCTOR//
    student(student &);                  //COPY CONSTRUCTOR OF STUDENT CLASS//
    ~student()                          //DESTRUCTOR OF STUDENT CLASS//
    {
       cout<<"\nDESTRUCTOR IS CALLED!!!"<<endl<<"RECORD DELETED SUCCESSFULLY"<<endl;
    }
};
 
int student::cnt;              //DEFINITION OF STATIC MEMBER//
student::student()                //CONSTRUCTOR DEFINITION//
{
        name="ANAGHA NIRGUDE";
        address="SR NO.81 BABBAR SOLANKI \nDIGHI, PUNE";
        year="SE COMPUTER";
        div='A';
        roll_no=21042;
        mob=942329999;
}
per_info::per_info()             //CONSTRUCTOR DEFINITION//
{
       lic="ABD45656";
       dob="02/11/1997";
       bldgrp="A-";
}
student::student(student &obj)			//DEFINITION OF COPY CONTRUCTOR OF STUDENT CLASS
{
      this->name=obj.name;			//this is a pointer points to the object which invokes it
      this->address=obj.address;	//this-> can be written as name
      this->year=obj.year;
      this->div=obj.div;
      this->roll_no=obj.roll_no;
      this->mob=obj.mob;
}
per_info::per_info(per_info &obj)		//DEFINITION OF COPY CONTRUCTOR OF PERSONAL CLASS
{
     lic=obj.lic;
     dob=obj.dob;
     bldgrp=obj.bldgrp;
}
//TO CREATE THE DATABASE
//DEFINTION OF CREATE FUNTION
void student::create(per_info &obj)
{
cout<<"\nNAME : "<<endl;
cin>>name;
cout<<"\nADDRESS : "<<endl;
cin>>address;
cout<<"\nDATE OF BIRTH : "<<endl;
cin>>obj.dob;
cout<<"\nYEAR : "<<endl;
cin>>year;
cout<<"\nDIVISION: "<<endl;
cin>>div;
cout<<"\nROLL NUMBER : "<<endl;
cin>>roll_no;
cout<<"\nBLOOD GROUP : "<<endl;
cin>>obj.bldgrp;
cout<<"\nLICEINCE NUMBER : "<<endl;
cin>>obj.lic;
cout<<"\nPHONE NUMBER : "<<endl;
cin>>mob;
}
 
//DEFINTION OF DISPLAY FUNCTION
//TO DISPLAY DATABASE
void student::display(per_info &obj)
{
cout<<"\n***********************"<<endl;
cout<<"\nNAME OF STUDENT : "<<name<<endl;
cout<<"\nADDRESS OF STUDENT : "<<address<<endl;
cout<<"\nDATE OF BIRTH : "<<obj.dob<<endl;
cout<<"\nYEAR : "<<year<<endl;
cout<<"\nDIVISION : "<<div<<endl;
cout<<"\nROLL NO : "<<roll_no<<endl;
cout<<"\nBLOOD GROUP : "<<obj.bldgrp<<endl;
cout<<"\nLICEINCE NUMBER : "<<obj.lic<<endl;
cout<<"\nPHONE NUMBER : "<<mob<<endl;
cout<<"\n***********************"<<endl;
}
int main()
{
 int n;				//COUNT OF NUMBER OF STUDENTS
 int ch;
 char ans;
 
 cout<<"\nENTER NO OF STUDENTS :"<<endl;
 cin>>n;
 cout<<"\n***********************"<<endl;
 student *sobj=new student[n];				//NEW IS DYNAMIC MEMORY ALLOCATION OPERATOR, sobj IS POINTER OF TYPE STUDENT AND IT IS A ARRAY OF OBJECT OF SIZE n
 per_info *pobj=new per_info[n];		//NEW IS DYNAMIC MEMORY ALLOCATION OPERATOR, pobj IS POINTER OF TYPE STUDENT AND IT IS A ARRAY OF OBJECT OF SIZE n
 
 do
 {
	cout<<"\n Menu \n 1. Create Database \n 2. Display Databse \n 3. Copy Constructor\n 4. Default Constructor \n 5. Delete (Destructor)";
	cout<<"\n Enter your Choice: ";
	cin>>ch;
	switch(ch)
	{
	case 1: // create database
	{
		for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
		{
		       sobj[i].create(pobj[i]);
		       sobj[i].inccnt();
 
		}
	}
		break;
 	case 2: // Display Database
  		{
			sobj[0].showcnt(); 	//to display the total count of students
			//we can use any object of student class as it is static member function
			for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
			{
				sobj[i].display(pobj[i]);
			}
    	}
    	break;
	  case 3: // Copy Constructor
		{
			student obj1;
			per_info obj2;
			obj1.create(obj2);
			student obj3(obj1);		//invoking copy constructor of student info to copy contents from object 1 to 3
 
			per_info obj4(obj2);		//invoking copy constructor of personal info to copy contents from object 2 to 4
			cout<<"\n Copy Constructor is called ";
			obj3.display(obj4);
 		}
        break;
	case 4: // Default Constructor
 		{
			student obj1;	//obj1 is invoking default constructor of class student
			per_info obj2;	//obj2 is invoking default constructor of class personal
			cout<<"\n Default Constructor is called ";
			obj1.display(obj2);
 		}
 		break;
	case 5: // destructor is called
 
			delete [] sobj;			//invoking destructor and delete sobj dynamically
 		     delete [] pobj;		//invoking destructor and delete pobj dynamically
 	}				//end of switch case
 	cout<<"\n Want to continue:(y/n)"	     ;
 	cin>>ans;
  }while(ans=='y') 	;
 
 
 return 0;
}

04/02/23, 18:56 - Divyam: Dear Friends,
Greetings from PICT!!
Impetus and Concepts (InC) is an Intercollegiate International Level, Flagship technical mega event of Pune Institute of Computer Technology (PICT). Prizes worth 7 Lacs, On spot job offers, Internship opportunities, Special Prizes for Rural Participants, Interaction with Industry experts, Patent Registration Fees for product based top quality projects are the main opportunities for Students...

Impetus( First year - third year students)
Impetus is an inter-collegiate international-level competition.
First year to Third Year students from various colleges showcase their projects. You can participate in a group of 2 to maximum 5 members. The project can be from the various domains like : Application development, Database, System Applications,Machine Learning, Pattern Recognition, Artificial Intelligence, Embedded systems , VLSI , IOT etc.
https://pictinc.org/impetus_register23/

Concepts (only for final year students)
Concepts, an international intercollegiate competition, has drawn major corporations for sponsorship as well as support they offers on-site employment offers and internships as well as guidance and mentoring for participants' high-quality projects and products.
The project may fall under a variety of categories, such as application development, database management, system applications, machine learning, pattern recognition, artificial intelligence, embedded systems, VLSI, and IOT.
https://pictinc.org/concepts_register23/index_org.php

Pradnya
PRADNYA is a one of a kind programming event. This Contest puts the programmerâ€™s logical thinking and Problem solving skills to the test using programming languages, which guarantees to appraise their skills. The maximum number of members in a team is 2.
https://pictinc.org/subevents_register23/online/index_org.php

Thanks and Regards
InC Student Coordination Team

The project is running at leading *campuses* including *IIM Ahmedabad, IIT Bombay, IIT Delhi, IIM Bangalore and BITS Pilani* among others.

Benefits post completion: 
1. *Certificate of Work  Experience* as an *Equity Markets Analyst* and an *Investment Banking Analyst*.
2. *Letter of Recommendation*. The project includes *personalized mentoring* interactions for financial markets guidance and *live sessions* for investment banking.
3.  *Incentives*: up to Rs. 6000 (for top performers)

To apply, students can fill out the form below and we will get in touch with them:

https://www.finlatics.com/pevc_combo/application/index.php?utm_src=mitwpuw

*Project Duration*: 2 months

*Project Start*: Flexible on student choice

*Project Breaks*: Selected students will be eligible for a break during the project if they need it for any exams, assignments, or personal commitments. 

*No prerequisites* or prior domain knowledge are required to be a part of this project

If selected, the program has a minimal induction fee: Rs. 1999 + GST / Rs. 3998 + GST (on student choice)

*Fee Waiver*: A *fee waiver* in the range of *25 - 45%* shall be given to all *MIT-WPU* students on the abovementioned minimal induction fee. This waiver will *reduce the fee* to Rs. 1499 + GST / Rs. 2199 + GST.

28/02/23, 20:19 - Shashwat Singhal: Hi everyone,
We need to insert values into our 5 ERD schemas(databases). 

Databases were Bank, Hotel, University, Course and Company. We already have tables with necessary constraints in it. We need to add 5 values in every table of every database. 

For example we have 5 databases, and each database has 5 tables approx., so we have total 25 tables. Now we need to insert 5 values in each table, so we would have 125 queries in all. 

We also need to create questions for each database. For example, we need to use DELETE and UPDATE commands to change existing values of tables.

I think I have got everything ğŸ˜‚. But ma'am would be better able to help us ğŸ¤Ÿ.

section .data
	
	arr times 64 db 0   ;Just like duplicate instruction arr DB ;34 DUP(0)
	;arr db 10h,20h,30h,40h,50h;arr1 db "10,20,30,40,50",10
	;arr1len equ $-arr1
	msg2 db "The  elements of array: ",10
	msg2len equ $-msg2
	msg1 db "Sum of array: ",10
	msg1len equ $-msg1

	cnt db 5
	
	temp1 db 0  ; Display output one by one

section .bss
	sum resb 2
	num resb 3  ; Store entered 2 digit Hex number 
	temp resb 2  ; After rotating by 4 store value Ax=1234h-> ;2341h

section .text
	global _start
_start:

	mov rbp, arr  ;added nw	
	
nextnum:rw 1,1, msg2,msg2len  ;The  elements of array
	rw 0,0, num,3
	Mov rcx,0
	Mov rax,0
	Mov rsi,num
up:Mov cl,byte[rsi]
	Cmp cl,0aH
	Je packed
	Cmp cl,39h
	Jbe down
	Sub cl,07h
down: sub cl,30H
	Rol al,4
	Add al,cl
	Inc rsi
	Jmp up

packed:	mov byte[rbp],al
	inc rbp
	dec byte[cnt]
	jnz nextnum


	mov rsi,arr
	mov ax,00h
	mov bx,0h
	mov cx,5		
up2:	mov bl,byte[rsi]
  	add ax,bx
	jnc skip
	inc ah
skip:	 
	inc rsi
	dec cx
	jnz up2
	
	mov word[sum],ax
	rw 1,1, msg1,msg1len  ;Sum of array:
	call disp
	

exit:	mov rax,60
	mov rdi,0
	syscall

disp:
	
	mov bp,4
	mov ax,word[sum] 
up1:	rol ax,4
	mov [temp],ax
	and ax,0fh
	cmp al,09
	jbe down1
	add al,07
down1:	add al,30h
	mov [temp1],al
	rw 1,1,temp1,1

	mov ax,word[temp]
	dec bp
	jnz up1
	ret

16/03/23, 12:31 - Panda ğŸ¼: Sorting: The sort() algorithm is used to sort elements in a container in ascending or descending order. This algorithm can be applied to any container that has random access iterators, including vectors and arrays.

Searching: The find() algorithm is used to search for a specific element within a container. This algorithm can be applied to any container that has forward iterators, including lists.

Transformations: The transform() algorithm is used to apply a function to each element in a container, and store the results in a new container. This algorithm can be applied to any container that has input and output iterators, including vectors and lists.

Removing elements: The remove() algorithm is used to remove all elements in a container that match a specified value. This algorithm can be applied to any container that has forward iterators, including lists.

Merging: The merge() algorithm is used to merge two sorted containers into a single sorted container. This algorithm can be applied to any container that has bidirectional iterators, including vectors and lists.

Rearranging elements: The reverse() algorithm is used to reverse the order of elements in a container. This algorithm can be applied to any container that has bidirectional iterators, including vectors and lists.

Partitioning: The partition() algorithm is used to partition the elements in a container based on a specified criterion. This algorithm can be applied to any container that has bidirectional iterators, including vectors and lists.

Numeric operations: The accumulate() algorithm is used to perform a mathematical operation on a range of elements in a container. This algorithm can be applied to any container that has input iterators, including vectors and arrays.

21/03/23, 09:41 - Harsh: //defining pins for the inputs and outputs
const int gas_input = A0;
int sensorValue = 0;
const int led = 6;
const int buzzer = 12;

void setup()
{
 
  pinMode(led,OUTPUT);
  pinMode(buzzer,OUTPUT);
  Serial.begin(9600);
}

void loop()
{
  
  sensorValue  = analogRead(gas_input);
  Serial.print("Deteced Smoke range: ");
  Serial.print(sensorValue);
  if(sensorValue > 299)
  {
    Serial.print(" | Smoke detected!");
    tone(buzzer,100);
    
  }
  
  //analogWrite(led,led_out);
  delay(100);
  noTone(buzzer);
  Serial.println("");
}

€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€ The CCA Component for the 10 Marks Active Learning MAIoT Course based on Units 3 and 4 is scheduled for Tuesday, May 2, 2023, from 3:45 PM to 4:45 PM.

classroom. You'll be allowed to respond to the questions by using your notes.

active learning begins.

question and include the question number in their submission. Bring stapler
with you.

Dear Students
Warm Greetings from the Department of Examinations..!!!
Hope this email find you all in good health and spirit...!!!
The On-Campus Term End Examination Schedule of 12, 13 and 14th June 2023 will remain same as per the Time Table Published on University Website.

All students request to note and do the needful

Best wishes

12/06/23, 14:49 - Rohan Nair: Dear concerned students,
Pl note the following points while appearing for online on campus exam for Peace courses.

1) Code tantra login credentials of the students to be entered correctly.
2) Apple device users can use the safari browser.
3) The students should login into code tantra using Browser only, not using Code tantra App
4) Android  device to use Chrome browser only
5) The exam link is mitwpu.codetantra.com
6) The student should not use the MITWPU Entrance Exam site and the credentials.
7) Those who have forgot the password please reset the password today only by clicking on forgot password link. 
8) Login issues will not be entertained on the day of exam hence try to solve the issues today only by contacting to the codetantra support team.

Thanks & regards,
Prof. Dr. Vilas Kanthale,
CEO, FoET

This position offers a valuable opportunity to gain hands-on experience in Robot Operating System (ROS) development and contribute to cutting-edge projects. The internship tenure is 6 months, providing an immersive learning experience in the field of robotics. As an intern, you will work with a team of experienced professionals and have access to state-of-the-art resources and facilities.

Responsibilities:

1. Collaborate with the team to design, develop, and test ROS-based software solutions for robotic systems.
2. Assist in the integration and implementation of ROS modules with various hardware components, sensors, and actuators.
3. Contribute to the development of algorithms and software modules for perception, planning, and control in robotic applications.
4. Conduct research and experiments to optimize the performance and efficiency of ROS-based systems.
5. Participate in code reviews, bug tracking, and documentation to ensure high-quality and maintainable code.
6. Stay updated with the latest advancements in ROS and related technologies, and propose innovative ideas for improvement.
7. Work closely with the team to troubleshoot and debug issues, ensuring timely resolution.
8. Actively participate in team meetings, discussions, and knowledge sharing sessions.

Requirements:

1. Currently pursuing or recently completed a Bachelor's or Master's degree in Computer Science, Robotics, or a related field.
2. Strong programming skills in languages such as C++ and Python.
3. Familiarity with Robot Operating System (ROS) and its core concepts.
4. Knowledge of robotic systems, including perception, planning, and control.
5. Experience with ROS packages, tools, and libraries, such as ROS Navigation Stack, Gazebo, and MoveIt.
6. Proficiency in software development practices, including version control (e.g., Git) and collaborative tools.
7. Ability to work independently as well as in a team environment.
8. Excellent problem-solving, analytical thinking, and communication skills.
9. Location: Chinchwad or Chakan, depending on work allocation.

Perks and Benefits:

1. Stipend: We offer a competitive stipend for the duration of the internship.
2. Letter of Recommendation: Upon successful completion of the internship, you will receive a personalized letter of recommendation highlighting your contributions and achievements.
3. Certificate of Completion: You will be awarded a certificate upon the successful conclusion of the internship, recognizing your expertise in ROS development.
4. Hybrid Work Environment: The internship provides flexibility with a hybrid work model, allowing you to work both remotely and in our state-of-the-art facilities.

Please submit your resume, along with any relevant project work or code samples, for consideration. We look forward to welcoming you to our team and providing you with a rewarding and enriching experience in ROSÂ development.

Please mail us your resume or WhatsApp via -
Mail us at: ericrobotics@premierseals.in

Contact Numbers:

We will use following guidelines for our department to plan academics on Monday, Wednesday and Thursday for this week only. (All online sessions)

Pl convey visiting faculty that there is change in schedule in this week. 

Monday: 
Schedule sessions of all courses of visiting faculty+ keep the option open if any regular faculty want to conduct sessions, they can plan and conduct, theory as well as lab. 

Wednesday: 1session each for all courses + other courses if  you can accommodate.

Thursday: follow the pattern of Wednesday. 

Pl call if any point is not clear/ facing any challenge.

21/10/23, 19:42 - Anish Kulkarni: Dear Colleagues,

To safeguard and nurture the Mental Health and Wellbeing of our Students and Faculty Members, MIT World Peace University consciously announces the establishment of MIT-WPU Aakriti: Centre for Mental Health & Wellbeing.

Through the Centre, a team of experienced and compassionate counsellors will be offering Individual Counselling Sessions, Group Therapy, and Workshops to discuss areas like Stress Management, Academic & Non-academic Domains, Interpersonal Relationships, and Personal Growth, Financial Constraints. In addition to this, the Centre will also facilitate Peer Support Groups, Timely Seminars, Workshops, and Group Therapy sessions.

We are committed to safeguard and provide a safe environment for our students and faculty members.

A Google form is to be submitted to register for the counselling session. Link for the same is given below:
https://forms.gle/PBHYz4FuzdUL1kU56

Following are the details of the Counsellors:
 
Common Contact Number: 9049689898
 
1.      Ms. Neeti Sanghvi
neeti.sanghvi.ve@mitwpu.edu.in
2.      Ms. Pooja Adkar
pooja.adkar.ve@mitwpu.edu.in
3.      Ms. Preetika Deshmukh
preetika.deshmukh.ve@mitwpu.edu.in

MIT WPU Centre for Mental Health & Wellbeing has been set up at 601-A, 6th Floor, Ganga Building, School of Liberal Arts, where counsellor/s would be available according to the following schedule:
 
Monday, Thursday, and Saturday:           8 am to 6 pm
Tuesday and Wednesday                 :           9 am to 6 pm
 
Regards,
 
Registrar
MITWPU

30/10/23, 13:24 - Omkar: Tech Skills Readiness Assessment mandatory for TY students

Considering the rapidly evolving tech industry, we want to address the increasing demands placed on future job candidates. The industry's expectations continue to rise, making competition for placement opportunities even more intense.

It has come to our attention via feedback from our top recruiters that some of our students may have gaps in their programming skills, making it challenging to meet the industry's high expectations. Companies now emphasise not only your academic achievements but also your Programming and Logical Development Skills along with Soft Skills.

Understanding the urgency of this situation, the Department of Computer Engineering and Technology is pleased to announce the Tech Skills Readiness Assessment for our current Third Year Students. 

This assessment is designed to help you identify the areas of improvement in your upcoming placement drive and bridge any gaps in your skillset.

Date: Oct 31 to Nov 2nd 23
Timing: 3:30 PM to 6:30 PM.
Mode:  Offline 
Programming Language:
any programming language (C/C++/Java/Python) 
Evaluation: 
Implementation of industry problem statements, similar to placement exams. followed by a viva conducted by an industry expert.

Duration of Coding:You will have 2.5 hours to implement your solutions

Attendance for all students is mandatory.

Scoring a specific eligible score on this assessment will grant you access to the upcoming placement drive without the need for prerequisite clearances. 

Even if you plan to pursue higher studies and are not seeking immediate placement, taking this assessment is mandatory for obtaining a Letter of Recommendation (LOR)

        The Marks Distribution for AIES End Term Exam paper is as follows.  

1. Every Question is having two sub-questions (e.x. 1a and 1.b) 
2. Each sub-question  carries 5 marks.
3. Total 10 questions
4. Solve any 7 question, each  question is for 10marks.
5. End term exam is for 70 marks and descriptive. 

Marks distributions acording to syllabus is given below. 

Unit 1-10
Unit 2-20
Unit 3-30
Unit 4-20
Unit 5-20

All the best for your exam.

23) Benefits that we get from data warehouse 
24) Necessity of data warehouse ( why isnt Relational enough ) 
25) Top down data warehouse design process
26) example related to covariance and correlation

13/01/24, 19:05 - Rohan Nair: Dear Students of T. Y. B. Tech. CSE_Panel _C___,
Greetings from Department of Computer Engineering and tb Technology (DCET)!!!!!!

We are excited to announce a two-week National Academic Immersion Program (NAIP) designed for Third Year B. Tech. CSE - Panel C students. The program is scheduled to take place from  5th March 2024 -   16th March 2024  at  RV University, Bangalore

Hence, the students are requested to fill the google form on or before 15/01/2024, 12.00pm to express their interest in participating in NAIP.

Please carefully read all instructions pertaining to the Parent Undertaking and Student Undertaking before filling out the Google Form.

 

1.     Field in google form:

 

1.       Name as per Aadhar card

2.       Gender

3.       Panel Name

4.       Roll No (Panel Name_Number)

5.       PRN

6.       Date of Birth

7.       Age on date

8.       Blood group

9.       Aadhar card number

10.   Personal Mobile Number

11.   Email Address (official)

12.   Local Address

13.   Permanent Address

14.   Emergency contact number1 and Relation

15.   Emergency contact number2 and Relation

16.   Upload_Parent Undertaking.pdf

17.   Upload_Student Undertaking.pdf

18.   Upload_Aadhar card.pdf

19.   Upload_Student MITWPU ID.pdf

20.   Recent Photograph(.jpeg)

 

Google form will be shared soon.
